---
import CalculatorPage from "../../components/CalculatorPage.astro";
import RetirementCalc from "../../components/calculators/RetirementCalc.tsx";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is a FIRE number?",
    a: "Your FIRE (Financial Independence, Retire Early) number is the size of the nest egg that can fund your lifestyle indefinitely. A common rule of thumb divides your desired annual spending by a safe withdrawal rate of 4% — so $60,000 a year ÷ 0.04 = $1.5 million.",
  },
  {
    q: "What is the 4% rule?",
    a: "It's a guideline suggesting you can withdraw about 4% of your portfolio in your first year of retirement, then adjust for inflation each year, with a high chance the money lasts 30+ years. It's a starting point, not a guarantee — markets and lifespans vary.",
  },
  {
    q: "Does this account for inflation?",
    a: "Yes. The income you enter is in today's dollars, and the calculator grows your target by an assumed inflation rate to your retirement date, so the FIRE number reflects future prices.",
  },
  {
    q: "What return rate should I assume?",
    a: "A diversified portfolio has historically returned roughly 7% per year after inflation over long periods, but returns are volatile and not guaranteed. Using a conservative figure builds in a safety margin.",
  },
];
---

<CalculatorPage
  slug="retirement"
  heading="Retirement & FIRE Calculator"
  intro="Project your nest egg, find the number you need to retire (your FIRE number), and see at a glance whether you're on track — adjusted for inflation."
  placement="retirement"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <RetirementCalc slot="calculator" client:load />

  <Fragment slot="content">
    <h2>Two questions this answers</h2>
    <p>
      Retirement planning comes down to two numbers: <strong>how much you'll
      have</strong> and <strong>how much you'll need</strong>. The calculator
      projects the first by growing your current savings and monthly contributions
      at your expected return. It estimates the second by inflating your desired
      income to your retirement date and dividing by a safe withdrawal rate.
    </p>

    <h2>Why starting early wins</h2>
    <p>
      Because of compounding, the contributions you make in your 20s and 30s do far
      more work than the ones you make in your 50s. Try shifting your current age
      down a few years in the calculator — the projected balance jumps, even with
      the same monthly amount. That's decades of extra compounding.
    </p>

    <h2>If you're behind, you have levers</h2>
    <p>
      A shortfall isn't the end of the story. You can increase contributions, work
      a few years longer (which both adds savings and shortens the drawdown
      period), trim your target spending, or use tax-advantaged accounts like a
      401(k) or IRA to keep more of your returns. Adjust the inputs to see which
      lever moves your number the most.
    </p>

    <h2>About the 4% rule</h2>
    <p>
      The 4% safe-withdrawal rate comes from research on historical market returns.
      It's a useful planning anchor, but real retirements are messier — sequence of
      returns, healthcare, and lifespan all matter. Treat the FIRE number as a
      target to aim for, then revisit your plan regularly.
    </p>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorPage>
